CP07 - BMW vs. Volkswagen

Diego Senso González

13/12/2020

Objetivo

El objetivo del presente informe es realizar un modelo Causal Impact entre las series temporales del precio de la acción de las empresas BMW y Volkswagen.

Modelo Causal Impact

Para realizar este modelo entre las series temporales de estas empresas se extraen los datos de cotización de ambas (desde el 1 de enero de 2014 hasta el 12 de diciembre de 2020), y se selecciona el precio ajustado que será con el que se trabaje. A continuación, visualizamos la series por separado:

De cara a estimar el modelo causal, seleccionamos una fecha concreta que será el momento en el que se destapó el Dieselgate. En septiembre de 2015, se descubrió que Volkswagen había estado utilizando ilegalmente un software que alteraba los resultados de las emisiones de gases contaminantes de sus vehículos. Por ello, se elige la fecha del 1 de septiembre de 2015 como el punto de corte para realizar este modelo.

Haciendo un “summary” se pueden observar las principales métricas del modelo construido:

## Posterior inference {CausalImpact}
## 
##                          Average        Cumulative      
## Actual                   131            175535          
## Prediction (s.d.)        152 (17)       203778 (23101)  
## 95% CI                   [119, 188]     [159859, 251517]
##                                                         
## Absolute effect (s.d.)   -21 (17)       -28244 (23101)  
## 95% CI                   [-57, 12]      [-75982, 15676] 
##                                                         
## Relative effect (s.d.)   -14% (11%)     -14% (11%)      
## 95% CI                   [-37%, 7.7%]   [-37%, 7.7%]    
## 
## Posterior tail-area probability p:   0.10911
## Posterior prob. of a causal effect:  89%
## 
## For more details, type: summary(impact, "report")

También se puede visualizar:

En color negro se puede visualizar la cotización de Volkswagen y su acusada caída a raíz del Dieselgate. Por contra, se observa que en color azul la predicción que realiza el modelo en caso de no haber existido intervención. Los resultados habrían sido claramente mejores. A partir de este modelo causal, se puede generar automática un report con los datos extraidos del modelo. La gráfica acumulada muestra claramente el descenso desde que se produce la intervención.

## Analysis report {CausalImpact}
## 
## 
## During the post-intervention period, the response variable had an average value of approx. 131.09. In the absence of an intervention, we would have expected an average response of 152.19. The 95% interval of this counterfactual prediction is [119.39, 187.84]. Subtracting this prediction from the observed response yields an estimate of the causal effect the intervention had on the response variable. This effect is -21.09 with a 95% interval of [-56.75, 11.71]. For a discussion of the significance of this effect, see below.
## 
## Summing up the individual data points during the post-intervention period (which can only sometimes be meaningfully interpreted), the response variable had an overall value of 175.53K. Had the intervention not taken place, we would have expected a sum of 203.78K. The 95% interval of this prediction is [159.86K, 251.52K].
## 
## The above results are given in terms of absolute numbers. In relative terms, the response variable showed a decrease of -14%. The 95% interval of this percentage is [-37%, +8%].
## 
## This means that, although it may look as though the intervention has exerted a negative effect on the response variable when considering the intervention period as a whole, this effect is not statistically significant, and so cannot be meaningfully interpreted. The apparent effect could be the result of random fluctuations that are unrelated to the intervention. This is often the case when the intervention period is very long and includes much of the time when the effect has already worn off. It can also be the case when the intervention period is too short to distinguish the signal from the noise. Finally, failing to find a significant effect can happen when there are not enough control variables or when these variables do not correlate well with the response variable during the learning period.
## 
## The probability of obtaining this effect by chance is p = 0.109. This means the effect may be spurious and would generally not be considered statistically significant.

Como se extrae del report, la intervención tuvo un efecto negativo sobre Volkswagen. Según el propio modelo, si la intervención no hubiera ocurrido el valor medio de esta empresa en el periodo postintervención habría sido superior. Sin embargo, el report indica que este efecto no es estadísticamente significativo y apoya ese hecho en el p-valor obtenido. A continuación, estimamos un modelo causal pero esta vez para ver los efectos directamente sobre BMW:

## Posterior inference {CausalImpact}
## 
##                          Average       Cumulative      
## Actual                   67            89298           
## Prediction (s.d.)        59 (6.9)      79095 (9297.9)  
## 95% CI                   [46, 73]      [61579, 98254]  
##                                                        
## Absolute effect (s.d.)   7.6 (6.9)     10202.6 (9297.9)
## 95% CI                   [-6.7, 21]    [-8956.3, 27719]
##                                                        
## Relative effect (s.d.)   13% (12%)     13% (12%)       
## 95% CI                   [-11%, 35%]   [-11%, 35%]     
## 
## Posterior tail-area probability p:   0.13747
## Posterior prob. of a causal effect:  86%
## 
## For more details, type: summary(impact, "report")

Gráficamente:

Como se puede observar, ocurrió el efecto inverso en el caso de BMW. A raíz de la intervención aumentó su cotización mientras que si no hubiera ocurrido la intervención el resultado sería claramente peor. La gráfica acumulada recoge el aumento de BMW a partir del punto de corte. Leyendo el report:

## Analysis report {CausalImpact}
## 
## 
## During the post-intervention period, the response variable had an average value of approx. 66.69. In the absence of an intervention, we would have expected an average response of 59.07. The 95% interval of this counterfactual prediction is [45.99, 73.38]. Subtracting this prediction from the observed response yields an estimate of the causal effect the intervention had on the response variable. This effect is 7.62 with a 95% interval of [-6.69, 20.70]. For a discussion of the significance of this effect, see below.
## 
## Summing up the individual data points during the post-intervention period (which can only sometimes be meaningfully interpreted), the response variable had an overall value of 89.30K. Had the intervention not taken place, we would have expected a sum of 79.10K. The 95% interval of this prediction is [61.58K, 98.25K].
## 
## The above results are given in terms of absolute numbers. In relative terms, the response variable showed an increase of +13%. The 95% interval of this percentage is [-11%, +35%].
## 
## This means that, although the intervention appears to have caused a positive effect, this effect is not statistically significant when considering the entire post-intervention period as a whole. Individual days or shorter stretches within the intervention period may of course still have had a significant effect, as indicated whenever the lower limit of the impact time series (lower plot) was above zero. The apparent effect could be the result of random fluctuations that are unrelated to the intervention. This is often the case when the intervention period is very long and includes much of the time when the effect has already worn off. It can also be the case when the intervention period is too short to distinguish the signal from the noise. Finally, failing to find a significant effect can happen when there are not enough control variables or when these variables do not correlate well with the response variable during the learning period.
## 
## The probability of obtaining this effect by chance is p = 0.137. This means the effect may be spurious and would generally not be considered statistically significant.

El report ofrece métricas similares al caso anterior, en este caso señalando que el valor de BMW habría sido más bajo si el Dieselgate no hubiera ocurrido. Sin embargo, sigue señalando que es un efecto estadísticamente no significativo y que puede ser una afectación espúrea.

Conclusiones

A la vista de los resultados,se ha podido observar que cuando una de las empresas se vio perjudicada por el descubrimiento de una práctica ilegal (Volkswagen), la otra salió beneficiada (BMW). Sin embargo, en ambos casos se reseña el hecho de que los resultados no son estadísticamente significativos.
